  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.11471" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <dateline>11, NORHAM GARDENS,<lb/>
          <placeName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.9">
OXFORD</placeName>.<lb/> 20 Aug. 1912.<lb/>
        </dateline>
        <opener>Dear Sir,</opener>
        <p>My friend <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1341">
Crum</persName>
          <note n="1" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1341">Walter Erving Crum</persName> (1865-1944), britischer Ägyptologe, vgl. HSA 02037-02066.</note> has written to me the good news that you are working upon <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.851">Nubian</ref> and more specially <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.569">
Meroitic</ref>, and that you are interested in my endeavours at decipherment of the latter but find it difficult to see my reasons for particular readings. I don’t know precisely what materials you are using.</p>
        <p>My materials are contained in the following: -</p>
        <p>
          <pb facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/>1) <bibl>
            <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.8561">
              <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Areika</hi>
            </ref>
          </bibl> by <persName>

Randall Mac Iver</persName> (Oxford 1909) (the inscriptions are reproduced in <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
Karanòg</hi>)<note n="2" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.8561">
                <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Areika</hi>
              </ref>
            </bibl>, by D. Randall MacIver and C. Leonard Woolley, Oxford: Letterpress and Plates, 1909 (Eckley B. Coxe Junior Expedition to Nubia: Eckley B. Coxe Junior expedition to Nubia; 1).</note> 2) <bibl>
            <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.8556">
              <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Meroë</hi>
            </ref>
          </bibl> by Garstang (Oxford 1911)<note n="3" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.8556">
                <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Meroë, the city of the Ethiopians, being an account of a first season's excavations on the site</hi>
              </ref>
            </bibl>, <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">1909 – 1910</hi>, by John Garstang, Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1911.</note> 3) <bibl>
            <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.7292">
              <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Karanòg</hi> Meroitic inscriptions</ref>
          </bibl> by Griffith (Philadelphia 1911)<note n="4" place="foot" type="editorial">Karanòg, <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.7292">
                <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">the Meroitic inscriptions of Shablûl and Karanòg</hi>
              </ref>
            </bibl> by F. Ll. Griffith, Philadelphia, Pa., Univ. Museum, 1911.</note> 4) <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
            <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.8555">The Island of Meroë</ref>
            </bibl> &amp;amp; Meroitic Inscriptions</hi> Part I by Crawford and Griffith (London 1912)<note n="5"
            place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.8555">
                <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">The Island of Meroë</hi>
              </ref>
            </bibl> by J. W. Crowfoot, London: Egypt Explor. Fund., 1911 (Memoirs / Archaeological Survey of Egypt. - London: Egypt Explor. Fund., 1911 (Memoirs / Archaeological Survey of Egypt. - London: Egypt Exploration Society, 1893-2008).</note> 5) Meroitic Inscriptions Part II by Griffith (London 1912).</p>
        <p>The last has long by ready but will not be distributed until next month. It contains all the Meroitic inscriptions from Napata to Philae and those from Museums</p>
        <p>
          <pb facs="#IMG.3" n="3"/>&amp;amp; one will remain to be published on inscriptions found recently at Faras and elsewhere.</p>

        <p>N° 5 contains many of the texts which have proved most valuable in the decipherment and I hope will provide you with the clues which you desire. But, as you know, I have made very little progress with the Meroitic language itself.<note
            n="6" place="foot" type="editorial">„Die Inschriften in <ref
              target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.569">meroitischer</ref> Schrift können heute transliteriert werden, viele Texte bleiben aber dennoch unverstanden, da die meroitische Sprache noch nicht entschlüsselt werden konnte“ (<hi
              rend="unknown" rendition="#none">wikipedia</hi>).</note>
        </p>
        <p>It is very gratifying to think that you are now occupied with these studies, and I trust that from your immende philological range you will be able to establish connexions with some definite group of languages and to explain the grammatical phenomena.</p>
        <p>I hope to publish a collection of <pb facs="#IMG.4"
            n="4"/> Old Nubian (Christian) texts before long in the Abhandlungen oft he Berlin Academy.<note n="7"
            place="foot" type="editorial">F. Ll. Griffith, <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.8559">
                <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">The Nubian texts of the Christian period</hi>
              </ref>
            </bibl>, Berlin: Verl. der Königl. Akad. der Wiss., 1913 (Abhandlungen der Königlich-Preussischen Akademie der Wissenschaften, Philosophisch-Historische Classe; 1913, 8).</note>
        </p>
        <p>If there is any particular question on which you desire information from me I shall of course be delighted to answer it to the best of my power.</p>

        <p>The connexion between Nubian and Meroitic seems to be slight: at least they are not the same language. Prof. <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2494">Reinisch</persName>
          <note n="8" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2494">Leo Reinisch</persName> (1832-1919), österr. Ägyptologe u. Sprachwissenschaftler, Prof. in Wien; vgl. HSA 09191-09341; 09341A-09355.</note> wrote to me recently that he is now convinced of this.</p>
        <closer>
          <salute>Yours very truly<lb/>
          </salute>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1643">F. Ll, Griffith.</persName>
          </signed>
        </closer>
      </div>
